We suggest that the decline in wetlands flora around Tel Dan (fig. S2) was the result of habitat desiccation due to reduced freshwater inputs to the marshlands, generating large areas of stagnant water, marshy borders, and brackish puddles (
 Fig. 4) surrounded by xeric vegetation types (fig. S2). The human populations that occupied the site during periods of low settlement density (~2500 to 1950 BCE, ~1050 to 850 BCE, and since ~550 BCE; 
 Fig. 4) inhabited a challenging environment and were probably subjected to marsh-related disease.
